<styl>RULERON<ql>
<styl>by <m2>By <m0>TED REED<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1>O<m0>ther airports want to eat Miami's lunch.<ep>
   For years, Miami has feasted on its historic dominance over traffic between the United States and Latin America. That dominance became even more pronounced in the 1990s, when Latin America's economies surged at the same time as American Airlines was focusing its massive resources on building a Latin American hub in Miami.<ep>
   Now competitors, particularly Continental Airlines hubs in Houston and Newark, are challenging Miami. Though chances that they could succeed in toppling Miami International Airport are slim, the landscape and the players are certain to change.<ep>
   But not immediately. Today, Miami's airport has 70 percent of all U.S. scheduled nonstop service to South America, and 56 percent of all service to Central America. It has four times as many flights to South America and three times as many flights to Central America as its closest competitors.<ep>
   It is also South Florida's most important source of employment, with 30,000 workers onsite and another 176,000 in related jobs.<ql>
<m0>Envy's understandable<ep>
<m0>   Competing airports can be excused if they are envious. They see that one relatively small, often congested, increasingly expensive facility (thanks to a $3.5 billion construction project) controls one of the most valuable markets in world aviation. And they wonder how they can get a bigger share of the pie.<ep>
   In fact, aided by the U.S. Department of Transportation, they can. The agency's oft-stated policy, in Latin America as in Europe, is to expand the number of U.S. gateways with nonstop, foreign service.<ep>
      Already, Continental plays up its ability to provide an alternative to Miami, in Houston. In various Latin American newspapers, it advertises daily flights to U.S. destinations via its hub at Houston Intercontinental Airport, which it calls ``the most convenient port of entry to North America.''<ep>
   In Houston, the ad points out, ``Your process of entering the United States will be rapid and easy, permitting you to connect to your final destination in as little as 50 minutes, compared with 90 in Miami.''<ql>
<m0>Continental looks south<ep>
<m0>  Continental continues to add Latin service. Last week, it was tentatively awarded a Houston-Lima route, complimenting the Newark-Lima route it began flying last month. <m1> <m0>The airline also plans to start service from Houston to Quito and Guayaquil in Ecuador in July and has applied to serve Sao Paulo, Brazil, from Newark, starting in December.<ep>
  In addition, the Colombian government is considering bids from American to provide daily service from Bogota to Kennedy International Airport, and from Continental to provide daily Bogota-Newark service.<ep>
   American will begin daily Dallas-to-Santiago, Chile, service in November, and daily New York-Rio de Janeiro service in June.<ep>
   ``Generally, the policy is to expand the number of gateways,'' said a Transportation Department spokesman, Bill Mosley. ``The goal is to break down restrictions, create new opportunities and liberalize service across the map.''<ep>
<m0>Similarity with JFK<ql>
<m0>   In a sense, what is happening with Latin America and Miami resembles what happened with with Europe and Kennedy International Airport in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ep>
   Historically, U.S. aviation gateways were established seaports, such as Boston, New York, Philadelphia, Los Angeles, San Francisco and, for Latin American service, Miami.<ep>
   But in the aftermath of airline deregulation in 1980, airlines began to build hubs throughout the United States. The industry and the regulators agreed that some of those hubs should have nonstop service to Europe, allowing passengers to bypass Kennedy, long this country's principal European gateway. They began awarding European routes to interior cities, such as Atlanta and Dallas.<ep>
   The biggest casualty of the policy change was Pan Am, a historic international carrier focused on Kennedy. It failed to build a domestic system. JFK's importance also declined somewhat, though the airport was able to enlist foreign carriers to fill the gap left as domestic carriers declined.<ql>
<m0>Miami meltdown unlikely<ep>
<m0>   Most experts don't expect a similar meltdown in Miami, largely because many Latin Americans actually want to come to Miami, while many Miamians travel to Latin America.<ep>
   ``Nobody is going to bypass Miami,'' declared Peter Dolara, the senior vice president who oversees American's Latin operations. ``The commitment American has to Miami is unparalleled.''<ep>
  Dolara conceded that American is adding a few flights to South America from Dallas, but explained: ``Continental is getting so big out of Houston that American has to have a reaction, as far as business that comes from the West Coast.''<ep>
  Still, it is clear that Miami's share of the pie is unlikely to increase (--) even if there are increases in service.<ep>
   Just last week, airport director Gary Dellapa ordered a study to determine the impact of the increasing number of flights between Latin America and other airports.<ep>
   ``Lots of places are getting flights to Central and South America, but does that erode Miami's market share?'' Dellapa asked. ``I don't know. Maybe it does in percentage terms, but not in terms of the absolute number of passengers, which has been increasing here by 8 percent to 10 percent annually.''<ql>
<m0>American could be key<ep>
<m0>   Some say the real impact of increasing the number of gateways will be felt in the future, when American offers so much service to Miami that other airlines seeking niche business will locate elsewhere.<ep>
   ``Right now, because we are in a period where airlines are profitable and expanding, you are seeing some route expansion at Miami,'' said Jim Laria, a veteran airport executive who is chief of cargo development at Orlando International Airport.<ep>
   ``But at some point, American will reach a pinnacle there, stop its buildup and maybe even cut back a bit,'' Laria said. ``At that point, no one else will be able to grow there, because of American's dominance. The other air<m2><ql>
<ql>
