PLANES,  FROM  23<ql>
<m0>lines will all be going elsewhere.''<ep>
   At the moment, the primary threat to Miami comes from Continental. The percentage of Continental revenues derived from Latin America has increased from 4 percent five years ago to 10 percent today.<ep>
   About half of the airline's Latin revenues are generated by service to Mexico, which Continental's predecessor, Texas International, began serving from Houston 30 years ago. Today, Continental flies from Houston to 11 cities in Mexico, eight cities in Central America and three in South America. It also serves Lima from Newark.<ep>
Recently, Continental has been recovering from years of poor labor relations, a reputation for shoddy service and an unsuccessful attempt to become a low-fare carrier. A key component of its growth strategy is additional service to Latin America (--) which inevitably comes at Miami's expense.<ep>
   ``Miami vs. Houston is something we've tried to play up,'' concedes Tom Anderson, Continental's vice president of marketing and sales.<ep>
  ``The No. 1 destination for Latinos traveling to the U.S. is Miami, where many have bank accounts, insurance agents, friends and family,'' he said.<ep>
   ``But since we don't have a hub in Miami, and we can't compete with American there, we feel as though we should try to develop our hubs in Houston and Newark and tell people that they can connect there as efficiently, or more efficiently, as they can in Miami.''<ql>
<m0>Houston touts advantages<ep>
<m0>   Among Houston's advantages, he said, are its burgeoning Latin population (--) the city is 25 percent Mexican American, with growing quantities of Central and South Americans (--) and its many connections to the West Coast, Southwest and Midwest.<ep>
   Continental is working feverishly to get more Latin traffic into its hubs. It is talking with carriers from Argentina, Brazil and Chile about moving their flights from Kennedy to Newark, in order to connect with Continental flights there. And it expects to one day fly from Newark and Houston to Cuba.<ep>
   Houston's Intercontinental Airport is a big supporter of Continental's effort.<ep>
   Central and South American traffic at Houston Intercontinental grew 6.7 percent in 1995 to about 670,000 passengers, up from 374,355 in 1990. ``Houston is now a proven gateway,'' said Hoyt Brown, deputy director of aviation. ``We just keep growing.''<ep>
<m0>Cargo, too<ql>
<m0>   Houston is also in the forefront of the battle to move Latin American cargo shipments out of Miami. Continued growth, however, is expected to make Miami's airport, which handled 1.7 million tons of cargo last year, the world's largest cargo airport within two years.<ep>
   In Houston, Latin American cargo carried in the bellies of passenger airplanes totaled about 5,000 tons in 1995, up from 2,200 tons in 1990. Several cargo carriers, including Miami-based Arrow, Challenge and Florida West, have expressed interest in Houston.<ep>
   ``Miami has been a victim of its own success,'' said Luis Perez, Houston's chief of cargo marketing. ``They grew so fast and so much that people are looking for ways to get products through without congestion and mishaps.''<ep>
   Houston looked on approvingly this spring when Dade County commissioners flirted with the idea of banning planes that use Miami International Airport from flying over Cuba, which requires that they pay a small fee to the Castro government.<ep>
   ``If that were in place, Houston would look even more attractive,'' Perez said. ``If it happens to pass, Houston can use that. It would add costs for many of the carriers who use Miami.''<ql>
<m0>Flower war possible<ep>
<m0>   Dave Rystrom, director of trade and development at Dallas-Fort Worth Airport, points out that delivering flowers and other perishables to Texas instead of Miami knocks 60 to 72 hours off delivery times to the West and Midwest. After Rystrom presented his case at a flower wholesalers meeting in Dallas last year, ``They invited me to dinner to talk further,'' he said. Now he has a deal with Miami-based Tampa Airlines for twice-weekly, all-cargo flights to Bogota.<ep>
   Dallas is also likely to increase its passenger business to Latin America, as American Airlines builds its Dallas hub.<ep>
   Other Florida airports want more Latin service, too.<ep>
   Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport thinks it can siphon off passengers headed for North Dade, Broward and Palm Beach.<ep>
   In addition, Fort Lauderdale-based Carnival Airlines is working to set up a connecting complex in Fort Lauderdale, where its flights from the Northeast could connect with flights to Latin destinations.<ql>
<m0>Carnival adjusting schedules<ep>
<m0>   Last month, Carnival offered a hint of its plans when it changed the departure of its daily Los Angeles-Fort Lauderdale flight to 11:30 p.m. so that the plane could connect with a Carnival flight to San Juan, Puerto Rico, and an Air Jamaica flight to Kingston and Montego Bay.<ep>
   ``We all know that Broward is growing by leaps and bounds,'' said Carnival Chairman Reuven Wertheim. ``As time goes by, we expect to attract more international travelers to meet our flights in Fort Lauderdale.''<ep>
   Orlando International Airport has argued for years that many Miami-bound passengers don't want to come here: They just rent a car and drive to Disney. Orlando officials say they are awaiting further loosening by the Transportation Department.<ep>
   ``We would like to see the market open up,'' said Keith Phildius, the airport's director of marketing and international development. ``It's still a very restrictive environment.''<ep>
   Orlando is patient, Phildius said. Only recently, Varig agreed to serve Orlando five times a week, with some nonstop flights and some service via Miami.<ql>
<m0>Fast-growing demand<ep>
<m0>   Aviation consultant Bob Booth, who specializes in Latin America, said demand in the region is growing so fast that traffic will grow in both Miami and in competing cities.<ep>
   ``No one is going to pull out of Miami (--) it's too important,'' he said. ``But the growth continues to be staggering: You can expect the total market to more than double from 16 million passengers in 1990 to 36 million in 2000.<ep>
   ``What this means is that in spite of Miami International's $3.5 million expansion program, the airport simply will not be able to handle all the demand,'' Booth said.<ql>
